argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">A hallmark of tragedies is that you almost cert=
ainly recall where
you were=E2=80=94what you were doing, or thinking, or some meaningless gest=
ure that you were performing=E2=80=94when you suddenly and irrevocably real=
ized that the world had changed. Perhaps you were watching <strong>Katie Co=
uric </strong>on <em>Today </em>on the morning of 9/11, as I was, or sittin=
g on your sofa chatting about quotidian details with your spouse when you l=
earned that <strong>Tom Hanks </strong>had contracted a bizarre new illness=
, Covid-19, while filming <strong>Baz Luhrmann</strong>=E2=80=99s
<em>Elvis </em>in Australia.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">I could tell you my =
whereabouts during the onslaught of Katrina, the financial crisis, the Indi=
an Ocean tsunami, Deepwater Horizon, or Fukushima. And that=E2=80=99s what =
I was thinking, in part, when I began following the dystopian surge of the =
Los Angeles fires on Tuesday evening from my office. It was about the scari=
est natural disaster imaginable, and yet it was somehow
occurring on familiar terrain, in proximity to so many loved ones, partners=
, colleagues, and friends.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I know that I=E2=80=99m given to occasional b=
outs of hyperbole, but rarely are they so justified. This week, my partners=
 throughout Los Angeles were forced to evacuate, shelter in place, bring in=
 loved ones, and reassure friends and children that the city would get thro=
ugh this. What=E2=80=99s more: miraculously, and undeterred, they
produced some of the best work imaginable, both about the tragedy at hand a=
nd not. And it=E2=80=99s worth resurfacing their incredible contributions, =
composed so heroically, because it is a testament to their craft and determ=
ination.</p></div>
